%I A397462 #21 Jul 11 2026 17:34:43
%S A397462 0,1,1,4,4,8,4,12,4,16,20,4,20,8,8,12,8,16,33,4,24,4,28,4,32,68,4,36,
%T A397462 4,40,4,44,4,48,52,4,52,8,20,12,12,16,181,4,56,4,60,4,64,125,4,68,8,
%U A397462 24,8,28,8,32,280,4,72,4,76,4,80,124,4,84,4,88,4,92,4
%N A397462 a(n) is the number of pairs 0 <= k,m < n such that a(n-1) = a(k)*a(m), with a(0) = 0.
%C A397462 As the sequence starts 0,1,1,... the smallest number possible there after is 4. So we know that the numbers that follow immediately after any 4 progress in multiples of 4.
%C A397462 The same reasoning holds for the successor numbers of any 8 and any 12.
%C A397462 It is maybe interesting to investigate the first appearance of terms that are not a multiple of four. We find a(1562) = 5, then a(601) = 6, but 7 was not yet seen in the first 10000 terms.
%C A397462 If we would not allow to count the cases where k and/or m = n-1, such sequence would start s(n) = 0,0,3,0,14,... = -2+n+(3/4)*n^2 for even n and 0 for odd n. This pattern may break as soon there exists any number that can be expressed as a product of other such numbers > 0 in such a sequence.
%e A397462 a(3) = 4 because: a(2) = 1 = a(1)*a(1) = a(2)*a(2) = a(1)*a(2) = a(2)*a(1).
%o A397462 (PARI) ListA(max_n) = {my(M=Map(), v=[0], c=0, p=0);  while(#v<max_n, for(k=1, #v, c=0; p=v[#v]*v[k]; mapisdefined(M, p, &c); mapput(~M, p, c+1+(k<>#v))); c=0; mapisdefined(M, v[#v], &c); v=concat(v, c)); v}
%Y A397462 Cf. A395918 (same idea but with a(i) * a(j) with i <= j < n).
%Y A397462 Cf. A394611 (additive version that counts only distinct positions).
%K A397462 nonn,new
%O A397462 0,4
%A A397462 _Thomas Scheuerle_, Jun 26 2026
